erican fleet. They then examine new whaling techniques developed at the end of the nineteenth century, such as modified clippers and harpoons, and the introduction of darting guns. Despite the common belief that the whaling industry declined due to a fall in whale stocks, the authors argue that the industry's collapse was related to changes in technology and market conditions. Providing a wealth of historical information, In Pursuit of Leviathan is a classic industry study that will provide intriguing reading for anyone interested in the history of whaling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAgriculture. 0aBusiness. 0aWhaling. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aGallman, Robert E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGleiter, Karin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226137902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226137902.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles